We’re making an original FRENCH RECORD this year!!!!! Incroyable mais vrai. Here’s some of the first session. We went in with five loose demos. Just an A and a B section, maybe a guitar and bass line that I’d worked out in advance. Then we fleshed it out on bass, drums, electric guitar and a couple synths. This might be my favorite way to make music. Or maybe this is just the most exciting phase of the recording process - when you get to experiment and be free and not worry about anything. Lots more of this in 2023.

My demos are very...sparse. They contain MOSTLY melodies and not a lot of harmonic information. For this song, I wrote a vocal melody, a bass line and a guitar line. So, three melodies (which is a chord, let’s be honest). Most of the time though, I ONLY write a bass line and vocal melody, and then we go into the studio with the “demo” and figure out the chords on the spot. It makes it a more collaborative process when you haven’t figured everything out, and Jack always takes the song somewhere I hadn’t imagined.

“Julie” is the story of my first kiss. I was eleven, and my family had recently moved to France. To this day, I’m not really sure if Julie had a crush on me, or if I had a crush on her. I’m guessing there was something there. But at the time, being attracted to another girl wasn’t an option. There wasn’t even a category for it in my head. I spent a lot of my life not paying attention to that part of me. I assumed that all girls enjoyed kissing other girls. But it turns out…that is not the case. It’s still not totally comfortable for me to say the words, “I’m queer.” To talk about the fact that a person’s gender isn’t what determines my attraction to them. And it feels especially insignificant to say this as a cis woman married to a cis man - as someone who’s loved the same guy for seventeen years. But I’m saying it just the same, because I know that it isn’t insignificant. Whatever I’m afraid of putting words to is usually worth saying. So I hope that wherever you are, and whoever you’re into, you have someone you can talk to about it. ❤️

When Philip was producing this song he asked, “Is this supposed to be ironic?” I suppose it could have been. But no…it’s completely genuine. I was thinking of what it would be like to get to the end of your life and actually feel proud and at ease - like you did it. Like you did absolutely everything you wanted to do, loved everyone really well, were a good friend to yourself and to others. I tried to tap into what that would feel like. My theory is that if you want to feel good when you get to the end of your life, you should practice feeling good now. It may sound silly but I highly recommend congratulating yourself on a regular basis. “You did it!” Or if that’s too hard, just listen to this song and think about all the things you’re good at and the people who love you. Also, this seems like a good time to tell you that Pomplamoose’s French record will be called “Félicitations!” Coming Spring of 2024 🌷🇫🇷🥂
